<div class="prose">

<p>A policy-writing coach and <strong>Unit 4's voice + defense partner</strong> — used in Blocks 9 (recommendations drafting), 10–11 (Brief drafting + Panel rehearsal), and 12 (Panel day). Two jobs: it coaches your <a href="/units/unit-4/assessment-chennai-climate-brief/">Chennai Climate Brief</a> into the voice an actual Greater Chennai Corporation official expects — direct, audience-aware, recommendation-anchored, no academic-essay creep — and it role-plays the tough panel questions before the live defense: cost, feasibility, equity, science credibility. It treats policy-brief voice as a learnable skill, not innate. For the science underneath, it hands you to the <a href="/ai-partners/climate-modeler/">Climate Modeler</a>.</p>

{% include "partials/partner-launch.njk" %}

<h2>How to use this partner</h2>

<p>Start with your reader, not your draft — the Policy Aide's first question is always "who's your reader, and what do you want them to do after reading?" Then paste a section and it suggests specific edits rather than rewriting for you. For Recommendations it pushes for who-acts, when, what it costs, who benefits, who's burdened. Before the Panel, ask it to play a tough GCC official.</p>

<p>Two prompts you can paste in to get started:</p>

<ul>
  <li><em>"Here's my Executive Summary draft. Tell me where it reads as academic essay instead of policy brief, and what specifically to change."</em></li>
  <li><em>"Play a skeptical GCC official. Ask me the hardest cost and feasibility questions about my top recommendation, one at a time."</em></li>
</ul>

<h2>Opening message</h2>

<blockquote>"Hi — I'm the Policy Aide. What part of your Climate Brief are you working on? Before we draft, tell me: who's your reader (a Greater Chennai Corporation official?), and what do you want them to do after reading? Audience focus is the whole game here."</blockquote>

<h2>Example exchange — what working looks like</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>You</th><th>The Policy Aide</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>Here's my Executive Summary draft. <em>"The science is clear that climate change poses significant challenges to Chennai requiring urgent action."</em></td>
      <td>Honest feedback: that sentence is academic-essay voice. "The science is clear," "significant challenges," "urgent action" — all general, all hedged. A policy-brief Executive Summary should be specific. Try this revision: <em>"Chennai faces three concrete climate impacts in the next 25 years: [name them]. This brief recommends [name the top action]. The cost of inaction is [specific consequence]."</em> Now: what are YOUR three concrete impacts and your top action? Let's build from those.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Watch out for</h2>

<p>Pressed hard, the Policy Aide can drift into writing the Brief for you — and words you didn't write are words you can't defend under Panel questioning. If you notice it generating your draft instead of editing it, pull back: <em>"suggest edits to MY draft — don't write it."</em> It should redirect to what evidence you have and what action you want the reader to take. Recommendations it proposes that aren't grounded in your evidence are the same problem: the policy reasoning has to be yours.</p>

<p>It can also get so focused on voice that it stops noticing whether the underlying science holds. The Policy Aide doesn't check science — that's the <a href="/ai-partners/climate-modeler/">Climate Modeler</a>'s job. Anything quantitative that survives into your Brief still gets verified against the IPCC or your cited sources, whichever partner it passed through.</p>

<h2>Before you go — documentation</h2>

<p>At the end of a substantive Policy Aide conversation, the partner will remind you:</p>

<blockquote>"Before you go — note in your <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation</a>: which voice problem did our conversation help you fix, in which section? And what's one suggestion I made where you decided to take a different angle — and why? That second entry is the evidence that the policy reasoning is yours, not mine."</blockquote>

